Daily Report 
<DATE1>  17 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ciller Claims PKK Force `Dwindling' Daily </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ciller Claims PKK Force `Dwindling' Daily </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA1705153994 Ankara ANATOLIA in English 1505 GMT 17 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA1705153994 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ankara, May 17 (A.A.) -- Prime Minister Tansu Ciller 
on Tuesday [17 May] said that the force of the terrorist PKK 
[Workers Party of Kurdistan] organization is dwindling from day 
to day. 
  `As long as terrorism is the biggest problem of the country, 
the fight against terrorism will rank at the top of the agenda,' 
Ciller said. 
  Addressing the True Path Party (DYP) parliamentary group 
meeting, she said that the PKK wants to spread new scenarios to 
the world public opinion, and for this reason defenseless people 
in the southeastern Anatolian region such as women, children and 
senior citizens were forced to migrate to northern Iraq forcibly 
by armed groups. 
  `These people had wanted to move to other regions under the 
security of the state,' she said. `All the world knows the pkk 
is a group of terrorists burning and destroying all the means 
provided by the state to develop that region.' 
  Ciller said she is once again calling on young people and 
their families not to fall into the trap of the terrorists, 
adding the state will continue to fight against the PKK until 
the terror ends. 
  She said the government is also closely following the 
developments in the region. 
  Concerning the Kirkuk-Yumurtalik oil pipeline, she said that 
Turkey is willing to solve the problem with a decision by the 
United Nations. 
  On the Turkish military units to be sent to Bosnia she said 
preparations are in the last stage. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

