<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-096 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  12 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   State Investigates Taping of Ciller Phone Call </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    State Investigates Taping of Ciller Phone Call </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA1205170294 Ankara ANATOLIA in English 1600 GMT 12 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA1205170294 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ankara, May 12 (AA) -- Ankara State Prosecutor 
Nazmi Sarvan on Thursday [12 May] said that an investigation was 
started following the telephone conversation between Prime 
Minister Tansu Ciller and two ministers from her cabinet was 
taped and leaked to the press. 
  He said the investigation will be conducted to determine 
whether there were any premeditations, or whether the 
conversation was heard and taped by chance. 
  Sarvan said that if it was determined that it was 
premeditated, the investigation will be conducted by Ankara 
State Security Court. 
  He said that there have been no initiatives undertaken by 
the 
Prime Minister's Office or the Chief of Staff's Office on the 
issue, adding the State Prosecutor's Office has used its power 
to start the investigation on its own authority. 
  The Turkish Constitution's Resolution No. 132 on crimes 
against the personal identity of the states [as received] and 
No. 195 on crimes on divulging state secrets would be considered 
during the investigation, he said. 
  A scandal broke out last week when a man listened to a 
three-way telephone conversation between Prime Minister Tansu 
Ciller, and two cabinet members. The conversation was recorded 
because one of the ministers was using his phone car. 
  In the conversation Ciller was asking her ministers to make 
necessary arrangements to extend the duty of the chief of staff, 
General Dogan Gures, for another year. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

