<F P=104>  Paris France-2 Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] A Libyan in Paris: The rumor went round Paris 
this morning and it was correct. The Libyan foreign minister 
did visit the capital last weekend. His presence has surprised 
and saddened the families of the casualties of the terrible bomb 
attack against the UTA DC-10. Philippe Boisserie reports: 
  [Boisserie] [passage omitted] For [Foreign Minister] Alain 
Juppe, there is nothing abnormal about this visit: 
  [Begin recording] [Juppe] [Words indistinct] not at all 
sudden, it has been his 10th or 15th visit over the last three 
or four years. I would like things to be clear. What is all 
this about? France has an extremely firm position -- perhaps 
the most firm position among all Western countries -- concerning 
the sanctions against Libya. 
  [Boisserie] What did he come for then? Do you know? 
  [Juppe] You will have to ask him, I did not see him. [end 
recording] 
  [Boisserie] The Quai d'Orsay [Foreign Ministry] added that 
it 
was merely a private stopover on his way back from South Africa, 
that there were no official contacts. However, among those 
taking part in the trip was someone who is not insignificant and 
who is of interest to Judge Bruguieres: The lawyer of the four 
Libyans whose extradition to France he has been demanding in 
vain. For the families of the casualties, this is too much. 
[passage omitted] 

