<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   FYROM Negotiating Procedure Enters New Phase </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    FYROM Negotiating Procedure Enters New Phase </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC1705072094 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 2100 GMT 16 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1705072094 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Dhimitrios Filios] </F>
  [Text] The negotiating procedure in New York for the 
resumption of talks on Skopje [The Former Yugoslav Republic of 
Macedonia, FYROM] has entered a new phase with both sides 
accepting a package for negotiation that includes the name 
issue. Ambassador Khristos Zakharakis, the Foreign Ministry 
secretary general, had a 90-minute meeting this morning with UN 
mediator Cyrus Vance. Afterward, Zakharakis simply said that 
views are being exchanged to find a way to promote the 
negotiating procedure. 
  Answering a question, Zakharakis said there is no progress 
in 
the talks but added that there are hopes. Asked whether U.S. 
Presidential Envoy Matthew Nimetz will participate in the talks 
and if there is a UN proposal that includes the term New 
Macedonia, North Macedonia, or Nova Majedonia, the Foreign 
Ministry secretary general said Nimetz submitted no proposals; 
he is merely participating in a procedure to exchange views. 
  Joe Sills, the UN secretary general's spokesman, today said 
there is no timetable for the talks on Macedonia. Vance will 
hold a new meeting with Skopjean Foreign Minister Stevo 
Crvenkovski late tonight, and tomorrow he is expected to meet 
Zakharakis. 

</TEXT>

