<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Inter-European Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Delors Comments on Meeting </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Delors Comments on Meeting </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR1705142594 Milan CORRIERE DELLA SERA in Italian 17 May 94 
p 2 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR1705142594 </F>
<F P=104>  Milan CORRIERE DELLA SERA </F>
<F P=105>  Italian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with European Commission President Jacques Delors </F>
by "A.Bo." in Brussels on 16 May: "Delors: Martino Wanted To 
Reassure Me -- But I Am Prudent, I Will Judge From the Facts" -- 
first paragraph is CORRIERE DELLA SERA introduction] 
  [Text] Brussels -- Jacques Delors remained cautious. Even 
after his personal meeting with [Italian Foreign Minister] 
Martino, the president of the European Commission was not thrown 
off balance: "The new foreign minister strove to reassure me 
that Italy will pursue its traditional policies in the European 
field. This is all. I have noted what he had to say," he 
stated to a small group of journalists in a corridor at European 
Council headquarters. 
  [CORRIERE DELLA SERA] Do you indeed feel reassured, Mr. 
President? 
  [Delors] I am a prudent man. Experience has taught me to 
judge from facts, not words. On the other hand, I do not want 
to call intentions into question. 
  [CORRIERE DELLA SERA] What assurances or guarantees have you 
requested from Minister Antonio Martino as regards the 
continuity of Italian policies? 
  [Delors] None. In fact, what articles of the Community 
treaties could I have invoked in order to put his Europeanism to 
the test? I am certainly not a teacher examining students and 
giving out marks. This is not my role. 
  [CORRIERE DELLA SERA] Early in the year you met [Prime 
Minister] Silvio Berlusconi in Brussels. Did you discuss 
politics with him, or did you receive him simply as a private 
businessman? 
  [Delors] Yes, I met Mr. Berlusconi, but only in his capacity 
as a businessman. Of course, I asked him for his opinion -- as 
a businessman -- of the economic situation in Italy. But we did 
not discuss politics. If anything, we talked about movies and 
Cinecitta [film studios in Rome], a subject I am very interested 
in. 
  [CORRIERE DELLA SERA] Are you now planning to meet 
Berlusconi 
in his capacity as head of the new Italian Government before the 
European summit in Corfu? 
  [Delors] There are no meetings scheduled. On the other hand, 
I believe Mr. Berlusconi's agenda is very, very full. 

</TEXT>

