<H3> <TI>   New Candidate Enters EU Presidency Race </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    New Candidate Enters EU Presidency Race </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM1805100494 London FINANCIAL TIMES in English 18 May 94 p 
22--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PM1805100494 </F>
<F P=104>  London FINANCIAL TIMES </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [David Gardner report: "Sutherland Ready To Join Race for </F>
EU Presidency"] 
  [Text] Brussels -- The race to succeed Mr Jacques Delors 
as president of the European Commission was joined last night by 
Mr Peter Sutherland the Irish director-general of the General 
Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT), who signalled he was 
available for the job. 
  Mr Sutherland, whose leadership at GATT was instrumental in 
securing the Uruguay Round world trade liberalisation deal, 
recently said he would be stepping down at the end of the year. 
  "If I was asked the question about being a candidate (for 
the 
Commission presidency) by a member state then I would have to 
give it serious consideration," Mr Sutherland said. 
  He told RTE, Irish television, that "it's an entirely 
hypothetical situation." But he stressed twice that "it's a 
very important position for Ireland, for Europe and the world." 
  Mr Sutherland's candidacy opens up a field which includes Mr 
Ruud Lubbers, the outgoing Dutch prime minister, Mr Jean-Luc 
Dehaene, the Belgian premier, and Sir Leon Brittan, the senior 
British commissioner in charge of the EU's [European Union] 
external economic relations. 
  The Irishman, a successful competition commissioner in 
Brussels in 1984-88, is a plausible if long-shot compromise. 
But he must pick up endorsements from leading member states -- 
particularly Germany -- and win the support of Dublin. The EU's 
12 heads of government are expected to decide on Mr Delors' 
successor at their summit in Corfu on June 24-25. 
  It is understood that of the larger member states, only 
Spain 
has so far sounded out Mr Sutherland. The GATT chief has a 
Spanish wife, and a Commission president from Ireland, which is 
a member of the "Cohesion" group of the four poorest member 
states including Spain, Portugal and Greece, would be a useful 
ally for Madrid. 
  Mr Lubbers remains the front-runner, but has less than warm 
relations with Chancellor Helmut Kohl. Mr Kohl is said by some 
leading EU officials to favour Mr Dehaene, who could also get 
backing from Paris. Sir Leon is hampered by being from the UK, 
which has opt-outs from the Maastricht Treaty. 

</TEXT>

