<H3> <TI>   Berlusconi Meets U.S. Envoy, Receives Clinton Message </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Berlusconi Meets U.S. Envoy, Receives Clinton Message </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR1605130794 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 2006 GMT 13 
May 94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR1605130794 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Clinton Sends Berlusconi Best </F>
Wishes"] 
  [Text] (ANSA) Rome, May 13 -- United States President Bill 
Clinton has sent a letter of congratulations and best wishes to 
Italy's new Premier Silvio Berlusconi on the formation of the 
new government. The letter was delivered to Berlusconi Friday 
evening [13 May] by the American ambassador to Rome, Reginald 
Bartholomew, and in it Clinton wished Italy every success in the 
renewal process underway in the country. 
  The U.S. President said he was looking forward to working in 
close contact with the Italian head of government to further 
strengthen the strong bilateral partnership that exists between 
the two countries. 
  Clinton recalled that he would be meeting with Berlusconi in 
Rome next month and again in Naples in July during the Group of 
Seven summit there. These encounters will offer excellent 
opportunities to develop that cooperation aimed at enlarging the 
democratic community, at spurring world economic growth and at 
promoting collective security, the message added. 
  During his meeting with Bartholomew, Berlusconi confirmed 
the 
intention of his government to work to strengthen civic society 
and political democracy in Italy. He urged that his government 
be judged on its actions and concrete results. 
  The premier also noted that the important international 
appointments in the offing will afford an opportunity for him 
and Clinton to take a deeper look at the many topics of mutual 
interest to them, also with a view to strengthening the firm 
partnership that already exists between Italy and the United 
States. 
  Foreign Minister Antonio Martino, who was present at the 
Bartholomew-Berlusconi encounter, will be going to Washington 
the last week in May to prepare for Clinton's Rome visit. 

</TEXT>

