<F P=101> Italy &amp; Vatican City </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministers on Conditions for Sending Troops to Bosnia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ministers on Conditions for Sending Troops to Bosnia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR1705085894 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 2021 GMT 16 
May 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR1705085894 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Bosnia: Previti, Martino, on </F>
Italian Peacekeepers"] 
  [Text] (ANSA) Rome, May 16 -- There was a chance that 
Italian peacekeeping forces might one day take part in peace 
operations in Bosnia but only if there were a unanimous request 
to this effect from the United Nations, and always within the 
framework of NATO, and in the presence of a bona fide peace plan 
to be safeguarded and brought to a successful conclusion, 
Italian Defense Minister Cesare Previti told journalists today 
coming out of a meeting with Reginald Bartholomew, the United 
States ambassador to Rome. 
  In response to a question, Previti said that in his talk 
with 
the American ambassador, Bosnia had come up only marginally and 
was barely touched upon. The U.S. ambassador, however, took the 
occasion to voice appreciation for Italy's "essential 
cooperation" in NATO's initiatives in and for the former 
Yugoslavia. 
  Turning to Italo-American ties, Previti stressed that the 
long-time alliance between the two countries would continue 
unfailingly in the future. 
  Meanwhile, out of Brussels, where the new Italian foreign 
minister Antonio Martino was attending an EU [European Union] 
ministerial meeting, the first signals were given that the 
Berlusconi government would like to play a more active role in 
the Balkan crisis. 
  Stressing that "the problem is very close to our interests", 
Martino announced to his European colleagues that an Italian 
diplomatic representation was imminently about to open in 
Sarajevo and would be placed in the hands of ambassador Vittorio 
Pennarola. 
  The minister did not rule out the sending in of Italian 
peacekeepers "under certain conditions" to oversee, within a 
NATO context, the implementation of an overall peace plan agreed 
to by all sides. However, Italy's controversial recent 
experience in Somalia led the government to want to be certain 
that it had a say in all the relevant decisions before 
committing peacekeeping troops to Bosnia, Martino said. 

</TEXT>

