<H3> <TI>   Confidence Debate Resumes; Miglio Criticizes </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Confidence Debate Resumes; Miglio Criticizes </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR1705103494 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 0923 GMT 17 
May 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR1705103494 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Confidence Debate Under Way"] </F>
  [Text] (ANSA) Rome, May 17 -- Sixty-one senators have put 
their names down to speak in the confidence debate which resumed 
in the Senate on Tuesday morning [17 May], official sources said. 
  Kicking off the debate today was Gianfranco Miglio, speaking 
from the mixed group benches in his first address since breaking 
away from the Northern League recently. Miglio said he would be 
voting in favour of the new government, but went on to criticise 
the government programme presented yesterday by Premier Silvio 
Berlusconi, and the stance of the Northern League. 
  Describing himself as "disappointed and amazed" by that part 
of the programme statement dealing with local autonomy, Miglio 
said that the government was aiming not at "federalism which 
guarantees liberty", but at "autonomy which covers centralism". 
  Miglio, until yesterday the Northern League's ideologue, is 
in favour of dividing Italy up into three macro-regions in a 
federative state. 
  The former Leaguer's defection from the governing Freedom 
Front alliance enhanced fears of a confidence debate defeat in 
an upper house where the ruling coalition controls only 155 
votes, against the 164 needed. A no-confidence vote by Miglio 
would have brought this down still further, to 154. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

