<H3> <TI>   Austria Promises To Support UN Human Rights Official </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Austria Promises To Support UN Human Rights Official </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1705131194 Vienna DER STANDARD in German 17 May 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> AU1705131194 </F>
<F P=104>  Vienna DER STANDARD </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report signed "est": "UN Human Rights Commissioner Visits </F>
Vienna"] 
  [Text] Vienna -- Austria agrees with new UN High 
Commissioner for Human Rights Jose Ayala Lasso, who demands that 
the Geneva-based UN Human Rights Commission hold a special 
meeting on Rwanda soon. The high commissioner, who was appointed 
at the beginning of April and had protested against the 
"genocide" there when he visited Rwanda last week, came to 
Vienna on Monday [16 May] on his first official visit abroad. 
  Foreign Minister Alois Mock promised the 62 year old 
diplomat 
from Ecuador Austria's full support, since the protection of 
human rights is "an important part of our foreign policy" and 
the "high commissioner is, casually speaking, a product of last 
year's UN Human Rights Conference in Vienna." 
  Asked by DER STANDARD how he plans to react to human rights 
violations, Ayala Lasso said he wants to "take a new path of 
seeking dialogue" with the governments concerned. If this does 
not help, there is still the traditional way of "pointing out 
and condemning violations and publicizing them." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

