<H3> <TI>   SPOe Objects To Mock's Remarks on Sudeten Germans </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    SPOe Objects To Mock's Remarks on Sudeten Germans </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1905092594 Vienna WIENER ZEITUNG in German 19 May 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> AU1905092594 </F>
<F P=104>  Vienna WIENER ZEITUNG </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Czech Republic Criticizes Mock"] </F>
  [Text] Prague -- The planned award of the "European 
Charles IV Prize" of the Sudeten German Landsmannschaft to 
Foreign Minister Alois Mock, Mock's interview on Sudeten German 
issues as well as the invitation for Czech politicians to attend 
the 45th Sudeten German congress in Nuremberg have given rise to 
harsh criticism in Prague. 
  By awarding the "European Charles IV Prize," which is not 
identical with the Charlemagne Prize awarded in Aachen, the 
Landsmannschaft next Saturday [21 May] wants to pay tribute to 
Mock's intensive work for "a just order of people and states in 
Central Europe." 
  On Tuesday, Prime Minister Vaclav Klaus expressed surprise 
about the fact that the prize will be awarded to Mock. He said 
in a radio interview that he does not believe this is an 
Austrian initiative. 
  An article by Mock in the latest edition of the weekly 
SUDETENDEUTSCHE ZEITUNG, the organ of the Landsmannschaft, has 
also caused some excitement recently, since the foreign minister 
came out in favor of establishing a dialogue between the 
Landsmannschaft and the Czech Republic. 
<H5>  The Social Democratic Party of Austria [SPOe] Distances </H5>
Itself 
  Mock's "shoulder-to-shoulder stance" with the leadership of 
the Sudeten German Landsmannschaft is not only an affront to the 
Czech Republic but also to the coalition's good neighbor policy, 
SPOe International Secretary Karl Schramek said. 
  Mock reacted to the storm of criticism by saying that he 
will 
continue to advocate the safeguarding of human rights and to 
oppose their violation. 

</TEXT>

