<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ruehe Hopeful of Accord on Bundeswehr Policy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ruehe Hopeful of Accord on Bundeswehr Policy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1905083194 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 0747 GMT 19 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1905083194 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Bonn (DDP/ADN) -- German Defense Minister Volker 
Ruehe (Christian Democratic Union) has described as good the 
chances of the Bonn coalition parties reaching agreement on a 
common overall policy for the Bundeswehr. After the first 
meeting of the coalition working group examining broad outlines 
for the future of the Bundeswehr, Ruehe said in Bonn on Thursday 
[19 May] that they agreed to meet again in June. He did not 
give any details. 
  The working group was set up by top coalition members after 
the differences of opinion between the Christian Democratic 
Union/Christian Social Union and the Free Democratic Party [FDP] 
came to light regarding future overall policy for the 
Bundeswehr. Given the current financial situation, Ruehe is 
aiming for a reduction of the Bundeswehr from 370,000 to 
340,000. Basic military service is to be shortened from 12 to 
10 months. Military service for the crisis reaction forces will 
be 12 months. The FDP has voiced its criticism over this. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

