<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kinkel: No Lifting of Arms Embargo for Bosnian Muslims </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kinkel: No Lifting of Arms Embargo for Bosnian Muslims </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1305210194 Hamburg DPA in German 1939 GMT 13 May 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1305210194 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] [Passage omitted] Klaus Kinkel [FRG foreign 
minister] stated at the new conference [after the Geneva talks 
on Bosnia-Herzegovina] that "the tragedy" in Bosnia, with the 
killing, rapes, and the devastation of the country, is 
unfortunately still continuing. Although progress has recently 
been made -- for example, the settlements for Sarajevo and 
Gorazde and those for a Croat-Bosniak federation -- the 
situation is still "fragile." 
  Both Kinkel and [French Foreign Minister] Juppe stressed 
that 
many obstacles still have to be eliminated on the road to a 
peaceful solution. Before German journalists, Kinkel was 
reserved in his evaluation of the results of the negotiations. 
"I do not want to be seized with false euphoria, we have so 
often been disappointed." After his talks with President Yeltsin 
and [Russian Foreign Minister] Kozyrev, he hopes for Russian 
pressure. 
  Referring to the lifting of the arms embargo for the 
Muslims' 
benefit, which is recommended by the U.S. Senate, Kinkel said 
that "10 of the 12 states of the European Union [EU] have 
problems with the lifting of the arms embargo." Moreover, in 
the UN Security Council, Great Britain and France would vote 
against it. On Friday evening, Kinkel also met with Croatian 
Foreign Minister Mate Granic in Geneva. [passage omitted] 
  While the agreement that was negotiated between Croats and 
Muslims and centrally handled by the Americans in Vienna 
apparently started from 50 percent for these two groups, the 
circle of ministers in Geneva agreed on a ratio of 51 percent 
for the federation to 49 percent for the Serbs. Thus, it 
accepted the ratio that was put forward by the European Union as 
early as at the end of last year. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-65594 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu097__a94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-097-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  19 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Germany, Netherlands Call For Strengthening CSCE </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Germany, Netherlands Call For Strengthening CSCE </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1705131594 Hamburg DPA in German 1212 GMT 17 May 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1705131594 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bonn/Vienna (DPA) -- On Tuesday [17 May] the 
foreign ministers of Germany and the Netherlands, Klaus Kinkel 
and Pieter Kooijmans, took the first steps in Vienna to equip 
the CSCE with the right to clear majority decisions. The 
German-Dutch initiative presented to the Steering Committee of 
the 52-nation CSCE was published by the Foreign Ministry in Bonn 
and is addressed to the summit of the CSCE heads of state and 
government, which will be held in Budapest from 7 to 9 December. 
  Kinkel and Kooijmans demand from the December summit the 
right for the CSCE to call on the UN Security Council, to work 
out recommendations, and to support their implementation by the 
United Nations if necessary also without the approval of the 
affected or defendant members. The two ministers voiced the 
demand for a considerable strengthening of the position of the 
secretary general, which is currently occupied by German 
diplomat Wilhelm Hoeynck. In certain areas he is to be able to 
call for majority decisions and to initiate himself immediate 
measures in critical situations involving members, such as 
observer missions. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

