<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN's Feissel, Denktas Meet 18 May </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UN's Feissel, Denktas Meet 18 May </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Feissel Reviews Meeting </H4>

<F P=102> NC1805210494 Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in Greek 1600 GMT 18 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1805210494 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Gustave Feissel, the UN secretary general's 
alternate special representative in Cyprus, held a meeting with 
Rauf Denktas in the occupied areas this afternoon. A statement 
Mr. Feissel made after the meeting indicated that again today 
Denktas did not give a positive reply on the implementation of 
the confidence-building measures. Mr. Feissel said that he and 
Denktas reviewed the Vienna meetings as well as the current 
state of affairs in the Cyprus issue. 
  Mr. Feissel further noted: I told Mr. Denktas that the 
preparation of the UN secretary general's report is in progress. 
He also said that he has sent material that will help the 
secretary general to prepare the report which, as Mr. Feissel 
noted, should be issued in mid-April. Mr. Feissel added that he 
will keep in touch with Rauf Dentkas. Responding to a question, 
he said that he is not going to send any more material to New 
York on the current situation. 
  Asked whether there was progress in Vienna--as Denktas, 
Ulucevik, and Madden had maintained in their statements--Mr. 
Feissel said: What is important is not progress or whether 
progress was made in Vienna but achieving agreement on the 
confidence-building measures package. This is what we worked 
for and this is our goal, because we will either reach an 
agreement or fail. Responding to another question, he said that 
again today there was no agreement, adding that today they and 
Rauf Denktas discussed many aspects of the packet, which he 
described as useful. He further noted that the secretary 
general's report will be ready by next week. He said that 
Denktas asked that they keep in touch, and added that until the 
secretary general issues his report Denktas has an opportunity 
to give a positive reply. 

</TEXT>

