<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Scharping Backs Lafontaine on Benefits Review </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Scharping Backs Lafontaine on Benefits Review </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1905160294 Munich SUEDDEUTSCHE ZEITUNG in German 19 May 94 
p 2 </F>

<F P=103> AU1905160294 </F>
<F P=104>  Munich SUEDDEUTSCHE ZEITUNG </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [`mes'-signed report: "Scharping Supports Lafontaine"] </F>
  [Text] Berlin -- SPD [Social Democratic Party of Germany] 
leader Rudolf Scharping has said that if he takes over the 
government, he will subject state benefits to continuous review. 
After holding talks with his financial and social security 
experts, Oskar Lafontaine and Rudolf Dressler, he said in Bonn 
on Wednesday [18 May] that this did not mean a lowering of 
social benefits, but an urgently required modernization of the 
state's social activity. In this way, Scharping was reacting to 
Dressler's sharp criticism of Lafontaine, who had announced that 
the SPD would also be examining social benefits to consolidate 
the state's finances. 
  Scharping said that the state's permanently increasing debt 
was strangling the budget, erasing the government's political 
room for maneuver, and turning taxpayers into debtors with the 
banks. "The SPD," he said, "will not continue with this policy. 
Instead it will subject all state benefits, including tax and 
social benefits, to constant review." 

</TEXT>

