<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rwandan Official Holds Foreign Ministry Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rwandan Official Holds Foreign Ministry Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1905223894 Paris Radio France International in French 2130 
GMT 19 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1905223894 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris Radio France International </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] France seems to be working on a major new diplomatic 
initiative in Rwanda. Yesterday, it was calling for the 
organization of a regional summit to end the genocide. Today, it 
was hosting Faustin Twagiramungu, the Rwandan interim prime 
minister-designate, who was appointed by the Arusha accords as 
representing a kind of third way between the Rwandan Armed 
Forces and the RPF [Rwandan Patriotic Front]. 
  Faustin Twagiramungu held talks this afternoon at the 
Foreign 
Ministry in Paris. A Foreign Ministry spokesman this evening 
revealed that there had been a broad consensus. According to the 
spokesman, the prime minister-designate insists on the validity 
of the Arusha accords, on condemning extremists on all sides, 
and on setting up an international tribunal to judge those 
guilty of the massacres. Twagiramungu will also see President 
Francois Mitterrand and Prime Minister Balladur. 

</TEXT>

