<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   New German Ambassador Presents Credentials </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    New German Ambassador Presents Credentials </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2005112194 Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in Greek 1030 GMT 20 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2005112194 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] President Glavkos Kliridhis has reiterated that the 
Turkish side has proved beyond any doubt that it does not have 
the political will to permit an overall Cyprus settlement. This 
lack of political will, he noted, contributed to the current 
deadlock in the confidence-building measures. 
  Receiving the credentials of new German Ambassador to Cyprus 
Friedrich Garbers, President Kliridhis said he appreciated 
Germany's position in promoting a Cyprus solution and 
maintaining UNFICYP [UN Forces in Cyprus]. President Kliridhis 
stressed: The people of Cyprus look forward to the day when the 
Nicosia wall will be demolished, just like the Berlin Wall. 
  Presenting his credentials, the new German ambassador 
expressed the conviction that mutual trust is necessary between 
the two sides and added that it should be built soon through 
measures such as those proposed by the UN secretary general. He 
also said that the German Government welcomes the European 
Union's [EU] recognition of Cyprus' European identity, thus 
confirming the expectation of full accession to the EU. Garbers 
is 62, and a career diplomat. He has served in Milan, Helsinki, 
Nairobi, and Rome. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

