<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Rejects Turkish Demarche on Training Kurds </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Rejects Turkish Demarche on Training Kurds </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC1905130094 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1130 GMT 19 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1905130094 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Greece has rejected Turkey's demarche claiming that 
members of the Workers Party of Kurdistan [PKK] are being 
trained on Greek territory. Government spokesman Evangelos 
Venizelos said the relevant Turkish deputy foreign minister 
summoned the Greek ambassador in Ankara and lodged a demarche, 
claiming that PKK members are being trained on Greek territory. 
  The spokesman stressed: Statements and demarches by Turkey 
that cause artificial tension have no meaning; Greece will not 
become an accomplice in creating an artificial climate of 
tension. Venizelos said: Greece condemns every act of violence 
and terrorism. There is no official representation of the PKK 
in our country. Greece is a pluralist state of law, with a 
legal order; whoever violates that legal order is punished. And 
he also noted that there is no reason for Turkey to attempt to 
export its domestic problems. 

</TEXT>

