<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bundesrat Outlines Priorities for EU Presidency </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Bundesrat Outlines Priorities for EU Presidency </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2005084494 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 0806 GMT 20 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2005084494 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Bonn (DDP/ADN) -- The Bundesrat called upon Bonn 
to deepen and strengthen the European Union [EU] during the 
German EU presidency in the second half of 1994. In that 
context, the government should in particular work toward greater 
closeness to the people, democracy, and strengthening the Union 
externally to allow the swift admission of the European Free 
Trade Association states. 
  Cooperation with the Central and East European states has to 
be moved forward, German must be recognized as an official EU 
language, and the European Parliament must be strengthened. All 
the laender endorsed a resolution underlining their joint 
responsibility for preparing "the important task of the German 
presidency of the Council." 
  Saarland Prime Minister Oskar Lafontaine (SPD) stressed that 
all those questioning European integration were jeopardizing the 
stability of the continent and facilitating nationalism. The 
most important task is to combat widespread unemployment by 
creating new jobs. Democracy also means access to work. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

