<H3> <TI>   Exports to Arab World Increase </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Exports to Arab World Increase </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1905202894 Hamburg DPA in German 1638 GMT 19 May 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1905202894 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bonn (DPA) -- German exports to the Arab states 
increased 2 percent to 15.8 billion German marks [DM] in 1993. 
The main importer of German products was Saudi Arabia, which 
bought goods worth DM3.6 billion (1992 -- DM4.2 billion) from 
Germany, the Federal Economics Ministry stated in Bonn on 19 
May. The United Arab Emirates replaced Egypt as second most 
important buyer, purchasing goods worth DM2.2 billion (up 26.6 
percent). Similarly high growth rates were reached in German 
exports to Syria and Lebanon. Exports to Egypt increased 11.8 
percent to DM2.1 billion. 
  German imports from the Arab states only reached the value 
of 
DM11.2 billion (down 7.3 percent). A good two-thirds of the 
imports was crude oil. Even though quantitatively, 1.2 percent 
more crude oil was imported, the oil bill decreased by 5.6 
percent to DM7.5 billion because of lower crude oil prices. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

