<H3> <TI>   Surplus in Latin American Trade in 1993 Shown </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Surplus in Latin American Trade in 1993 Shown </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1905133094 Hamburg DPA in German 1005 GMT 19 May 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1905133094 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bonn (DPA) -- As compared to the year before, 
Germany's imports from Latin America decreased by 15.1 percent 
to 12.4 billion German marks [DM] in 1993. All big Latin 
American countries were affected by it, which is shown by 
statistics published by the FRG Economics Ministry in Bonn on 
Thursday [19 May]. Smaller countries like Bolivia and Paraguay 
registered gains. 
  However, German exports to Latin America increased by 7.2 
percent to DM14.8 billion. For the first time after 1991, this 
resulted in a trade surplus for Germany again. 

</TEXT>

