<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   EU To Give New Laender Structural Funds by 1999 </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    EU To Give New Laender Structural Funds by 1999 </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1305123794 Hamburg DPA in German 1120 GMT 13 May 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1305123794 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Schwerin (DPA) -- The new EU [European Union] 
structural funds for eastern Germany will be made available as 
soon as possible. A group of experts will be set up to remove 
any existing problems of a structural improvement concept. This 
is what the minister-presidents of the new laender and the 
president of the European Commission, Jacques Delors, agreed 
upon in Schwerin on 13 May. 
  Since the beginning of this year, the new laender have 
formed 
part of the highest category of EU aid, the so-called target-1 
regions. From 1994 to 1999, they will receive a total of 
approximately 27.5 billion German marks [EU] from the EC 
structural fund. So far, it was not clear in what way and for 
what purpose the structural funds were to be used. The EU, the 
Federal Government, and the new laender have negotiated for 
months on a common aid concept for eastern Germany. That is why 
the EU funds could not flow into the new laender. [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

